<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-666-97> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Nachtspiegel met deksel van geslagen messing. De buitenste rand van het deksel valt in een groef in de onderste pot zodat een goede sluiting wordt gewaarborgd. Bovenop het deksel zit een kleine knop om het deksel te lichten. Dergelijke objecten werden dikwijls als huwelijksgeschenk gegeven.\r\n\r\nChamber pot for women. Like the other round containers made of brass, it was hammered into shape. The outermost part of the lid falls into a groove in the body so as to ensure a close fit. On top of the lid is a small knob for grasping when opening. \r\nThe chamber pot is a portable indoor toilet, used at night. It was not only a necessity for everyday life, but also one of the presents for the newly-wed couple. Some chamber pots were designed for women traveling long distances in a sedan chair. Cotton wool and paper in the bowl muffled awkward sounds.\r\nIt was usually made of brass or porcelain, but in the early 20th century, most of them were replaced as porcelain ones. Its use dates back thousands years ago, and it was widely used for every ranks of people.  The lid could be also used as an ashtray." .
